      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Parallel Execution Within a Fixed Plan"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Plan-Then-Act does not require strictly sequential execution. When the planner annotates dependencies between steps, independent steps can run in parallel within each topological wave. This is the pattern's most powerful optimisation \u2014 and it is only possible because the plan is committed upfront:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "import asyncio\n\nasync def execute_step_async(\n    step: ActionStep,\n    prior_results: dict[int, str],\n    tool_registry: dict,\n) -> str:\n    args_str = json.dumps(step.args)\n    for idx, result in prior_results.items():\n        args_str = args_str.replace(f\"{{step_{idx}_result}}\", result[:1000])\n    args = json.loads(args_str)\n    tool_fn = tool_registry[step.tool]\n    return await tool_fn(**args)\n\nasync def run_plan_parallel(\n    steps: list[ActionStep],\n    tool_registry: dict,\n    waves: list[list[int]],\n) -> dict[int, str]:\n    \"\"\"Execute independent steps in a wave in parallel.\n\n    waves: topological waves from dependency analysis,\n    e.g. [[1], [2, 3], [4, 5], [6]]\n    \"\"\"\n    index   = {s.index: s for s in steps}\n    results: dict[int, str] = {}\n\n    for wave_ids in waves:\n        wave_tasks = [index[wid] for wid in wave_ids]\n        wave_results = await asyncio.gather(*[\n            execute_step_async(s, results, tool_registry)\n            for s in wave_tasks\n        ])\n        for step, result in zip(wave_tasks, wave_results):\n            results[step.index] = result\n            step.result = result\n    return results\n\n# Example \u2014 steps 2 and 3 depend only on step 1 (can run in parallel):\n# waves = [[1], [2, 3], [4]]\n# asyncio.run(run_plan_parallel(steps, tool_registry, waves))"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The planner must include dependency annotations for this to work. Add a "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "depends_on"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " field to the planning prompt schema alongside "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "tool"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " and "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "args"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": ". The executor then runs the dependency analysis step before dispatching."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "horizontalRule"
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Handling Step Failures"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "When a step fails in a committed plan, the remaining steps may become invalid. A targeted recovery strategy replaces only the failed step and its successors with a new sub-plan, preserving completed work:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "def run_plan_with_retry(\n    goal: str,\n    available_tools: list[str],\n    max_replan_attempts: int = 2,\n) -> dict[int, str]:\n    \"\"\"Plan-Then-Act with failure handling.\n\n    If a step fails, a targeted re-plan replaces only the failed\n    step and the remaining steps that depend on it.\n    \"\"\"\n    steps = plan(goal, available_tools)\n    steps = validate_and_fix_plan(steps, goal, available_tools)\n\n    results: dict[int, str] = {}\n    i = 0\n    replan_count = 0\n\n    while i < len(steps):\n        step = steps[i]\n        try:\n            results[step.index] = execute_step(step, results)\n            i += 1\n        except Exception as e:\n            if replan_count >= max_replan_attempts:\n                raise RuntimeError(\n                    f\"Step {step.index} failed after {replan_count} replan attempts\"\n                ) from e\n            print(f\"Step {step.index} failed: {e}. Re-planning remaining steps.\")\n            # Replace failed step onward with a new sub-plan\n            context = \"\\n\".join(\n                f\"Step {idx}: {results[idx][:200]}\" for idx in sorted(results)\n            )\n            new_goal = (\n                f\"Original goal: {goal}\\n\"\n                f\"Completed so far:\\n{context}\\n\"\n                f\"Step {step.index} failed with: {e}\\n\"\n                f\"Continue from this point to complete the original goal.\"\n            )\n            new_steps = plan(new_goal, available_tools)\n            steps = steps[:i] + new_steps\n            replan_count += 1\n    return results"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "This hybrid approach keeps the pattern's simplicity for the happy path while adding graceful degradation for failures. The re-plan is scoped narrowly: it starts from the failure point with full context of completed work."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "horizontalRule"
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Structured Output for Reliable Parsing"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Planner output must be parsed into executable "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "ActionStep"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " objects. Using the Anthropic tool_use API with a JSON schema enforces structure at the model level, eliminating parsing errors entirely:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "OUTPUT_SCHEMA = {\n    \"type\": \"object\",\n    \"properties\": {\n        \"steps\": {\n            \"type\": \"array\",\n            \"items\": {\n                \"type\": \"object\",\n                \"properties\": {\n                    \"index\":     {\"type\": \"integer\"},\n                    \"tool\":      {\"type\": \"string\", \"enum\": [\"web_search\", \"run_code\", \"write_file\"]},\n                    \"args\":      {\"type\": \"object\"},\n                    \"rationale\": {\"type\": \"string\"},\n                },\n                \"required\": [\"index\", \"tool\", \"args\", \"rationale\"],\n            }\n        }\n    },\n    \"required\": [\"steps\"],\n}\n\n# Use with tool_use to guarantee parseable output:\ndef plan_structured(goal: str, available_tools: list[str]) -> list[ActionStep]:\n    response = client.messages.create(\n        model=\"claude-sonnet-4-6\",\n        max_tokens=1024,\n        tools=[{\n            \"name\": \"emit_plan\",\n            \"description\": \"Output the final plan as structured JSON.\",\n            \"input_schema\": OUTPUT_SCHEMA,\n        }],\n        tool_choice={\"type\": \"any\"},\n        messages=[{\"role\": \"user\", \"content\": PLAN_THEN_ACT_PROMPT.format(\n            goal=goal, tools=\", \".join(available_tools))}],\n    )\n    tool_use = next(b for b in response.content if b.type == \"tool_use\")\n    return [ActionStep(**s) for s in tool_use.input[\"steps\"]]"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "bold"
              }
            ],
            "text": "Why this matters:"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " if the planner returns malformed JSON, the executor silently produces wrong results or crashes mid-run. Structured output validation shifts the error to the planning phase, where it can be retried before any irreversible action is taken."
          }
        ]
      },
